    <title>Facebook and Instagram’s ‘pay or consent’ ad model violates the DMA, says the EU</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A graphic illustration representing the European Union flag." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/2Fw3jBX31UoMvirW8H1eZjlBhnk=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73437542/STK450_European_Union_02.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="VGFMni"&gt;The EU has formally charged Meta with violations of its Digital Markets Act (DMA), marking its second such charge in as many weeks. The European Commission &lt;a href="https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_24_3582"&gt;writes in a preliminary ruling&lt;/a&gt; that the “pay or consent” advertising model that &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/11/10/23955987/instagram-facebook-without-ads-eu-subscription"&gt;launched last year for Facebook and Instagram users&lt;/a&gt; runs afoul of Article 5(2) of the DMA by not giving users a third option that uses less data for ad targeting but is still free to use.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="18zwXE"&gt;Regulators found in their investigation that Meta gives users a “binary choice” that forces them to either choose to pay a monthly subscription fee to get the ad-free version of Facebook and Instagram or consent to the ad-supported version. Where Meta runs afoul of its rules, it says, is by not letting users opt for a...&lt;/p&gt;
